This paper proposes an algorithm for nonnegative matrix factorization (NMF) that is motivated by singular value decomposition and aims to identify features in realistic datasets. The paper discusses the theoretical result that maximizing the objective function corresponds to correctly classifying articles in a nearly separable corpus, which suggests that the paper could be relevant to the information retrieval (cs.IR) and natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper's focus on identifying features in datasets could make it relevant to the machine learning (cs.LG) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the computational experiments conducted in the paper suggest that it could also be relevant to the scientific computing (cs.NA) and social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
